We watched Ruby Bridges so our 6-year-old can learn about the world we live in and about its past. It may be hard to understand protests, but it is easy to see the pain of a little girl who had to be escorted to school by U.S. Marshalls because her skin is black.

Education must include history that text book authors leave out because it is too uncomfortable to talk about or doesn't fit in with the narrative of the majority group. Home is a great place for stimulating conversations and for answering difficult questions.

Although not based on colour, the tensions are similar in many ways to the majority minority relations in Sri Lanka where I grew up. Simmering tensions are ignored and suppressed until it explodes. Acknowledging the existence of problems is always a good start.
Life for coloured peple today is vastly different and we must acknowledge and appreciate it while at the same time recognizing the systemic injustices that change destinies and shorten life spans.

For Ruby Bridges, a 6-year-old in the States in the 1960's, going to school was a traumatic experience. Livid parents stood behind barricades at the school entrance shouting insults and holding placards because she was black and the school was for whites
